    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-06-26T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-06-26T13:00:00-05:00" n="247"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d247">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/12508: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador to the Polish Government in Exile</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Biddle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-26T20:00:00+02:00"
                            >June 26, 1941—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 26—4:23 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Polish Series [No.] 24. My No. 21, June 23, 11 p.m. General Sikorski
                    confidentially informed me that (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) in agreement with
                    British Government, Polish Government would adopt a wait and see attitude for
                    next 10 days with regard to Moscow’s reaction to Polish Government’s proposals
                    as voiced by General Sikorski in his radio address of June 23. Meanwhile Polish
                    Government would leave matter in the hands of British Ambassador, Sir Stafford
                    Cripps, and General Mason-MacFarlane,<note n="81" xml:id="d247fn81">Lt. Gen. F.
                        N. Mason-MacFarlane was the head of the British Military Mission which was
                        sent to the Soviet Union following the attack by Germany.</note> Chief of
                    British Military Mission, after their arrival in Moscow; (<hi rend="italic"
                        >b</hi>) Cripps and MacFarlane fully understood policy of Polish Government
                    and position of Polish war and civilian prisoners in Russia; (<hi rend="italic"
                        >c</hi>) Cripps would keep Ambassador Steinhardt fully informed of his talks
                    with Russian authorities.</p>
                <closer>[<signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Biddle</hi>
                    </signed>]</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
